Background

Electric scooter are commonly used among students and workers that want to either avoid traffic or save money by not using a car. There are different kinds of electric transportation devices that the company Segway offers. There is a great variety of features and specifications depending on the model, but what is the relation of the speed and the max range/distance(miles) that you can use the electric device like a Segway for local transportation?

Analysis

This analysis attempts to model the actual relation of speed and distance/range according to the specification reported for the different Segway models included in the data set by using a linear regression. Specifically,

\[ \underbrace{Y_i}_\text{Speed} = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \underbrace{X_i}_\text{Distance} + \epsilon_i \quad \text{where} \ \epsilon_i \sim N(0, \sigma^2) \]

Hypotheses

The hypotheses for this study contains the slope of the regression model, β1. If the slope equals zero, then the relationship between speed and distance/rage reported of the different Segway models will not be meaningful.

\[ H_0: β_\text {1} = 0 \]

\[ H_a: β_\text {1} \neq 0 \]

Significance Level

\[ \alpha=0.05 \]

Analysis

Graphical Summary

This is the scatterplot of the relationship between the Speed and Distance reported for each of the Segway models used for this analysis. The dots are very scattered all over the plot.

plot(speed ~ distance, data=segway, pch=21, bg="steelblue", col="gray", 
     xlab="Distance (miles)", ylab="Speed (miles/h)", 
     main="Speed/Distance Perceptions of 10 models of Segway", las=1)
mtext(side=3, text="These Segway models seem to to have very different Speed/Distance characteristics from each other", cex=0.8)
segway.lm <- lm(speed ~ distance, data=segway)
abline(segway.lm, lwd=3, col=rgb(.4,.4,.4,.2))
abline(v=seq(40,120,20), h=seq(40,120,20), lty=2, col=rgb(.6,.6,.6,.2))

This is the equation of the estimated regression equation from the scatterplot above is given by

\[ \underbrace{\hat{Y}_i}_\text{Speed} = 11.51 + 0.2246 \underbrace{X_i}_\text{Distance} \]

Regression Analysis

The estimated slope of this regression is 0.2246, which is different than zero (p = 0.06342).

Below is the relation summary table of the full linear regression results.

segway.lm <- lm(speed ~ distance, data=segway)
pander(summary(segway.lm))

Interpretation

The estimated value of the slope is 0.2246. It shows that the relation of Speed and Distance on average if a Segway is that increasing the speed by 11.5 mph (Y-intercept = 11.51) will result in an extra 0.2246 traveled miles from the initial point. The slope of this analysis is not significant (p = 0.06342). Hence the relationship of speed and travel distance of the Segway model used for this analysis is not meaningful. Segway offer different tiers of Segways, however, it seems that the speed vs max travel distance with one charge vary drastically for each model of Segway. The relation of Speed and max travel Distance might be related to the actual battery capacity and future studies including the battery capacity could be conducted to contemplate the relation and even to conclude which Segway model offer the best efficacy for local transportation. To verify the efficacy of this regression model, the requirement will be check below based on the appropriateness of the regression.

The intercept (βo) says that at a distance of 0miles, the Segway would go at 11.51mph which is completely inaccurate and shows how for this analysis the y-intercept by itself doesn’t say to much nor gives an accurate estiamte of the speed when x=0.

The prediction below shoes that if a Segway has traveled 17.04miles, then the predicted speed for that Segway would be 15.3mph based on the regression equation model of this analysis. \[ \hat{Y}_i = \overbrace{11.51}^{\stackrel{\text{y-int}}{\text{baseline}}} + \overbrace{0.2246}^{\stackrel{\text{slope}}{\text{baseline}}} * 17.04miles = 15.33718 mph \]

As we can see below, the square root of 0.367 is 0.6 which mean that the r relation for this model is moderate because is less than 1 but is not 0 or less than that. The correlation is visible as we see the proximity of the data pointa to the line in the graph that is displayed at the beginning of this analysis. \[ R^2=\sqrt{0.367} = 0.605 \]

Appropriateness of the above Regression

The Residuals vs Fitted (1st plot on the left) does not show a linear relationship and it is somehow questionable because it shows some outliers in points 10, 1, 3. We can’t see a constant variance or linear relations in this graph. The normality of the error terms needs to be assessed by considering a normal probability Q-Q plot of the residuals, for this analysis we can see that the second graph shows that the sample is right-skewed but we are looking for normality. Finally the Residuals vs order graph (the one on the left) does not shoe a visible trend as we see that the points are scattered, and there is one in the top right corner way distant from the others.

par(mfrow=c(1,3))
plot(segway.lm, which=1)
qqPlot(segway.lm$residuals, id=FALSE)
plot(segway.lm$residuals, main="Residuals vs Order")

Conclusion/Future Studies

There is no constant variance or linear relationship between the speed and maximum distance/range in miles that all different Segways have. The requirements of this linear regression are not entirely satisfied, therefor the test is not valid. However, we can say that on average at a speed of 11 mph, Segways can travel about 0.2 miles. It can vary form model to model and it might be related to the actual capacity of the battery. Future studies can be conducted including more Segway models and including reported distance travel at certain speed by different model or keeping into account the battery capacity for each model.
